3 18. Participation in parole board and pardon decision. Victims may submit a written
4 statement for consideration by the parole board, the governor, or the pardon advisory
5 board, if one has been appointed, prior to the parole board, the governor, or the
6 pardon advisory board taking any action on a defendant's request for parole or
7 pardon. A victim statement made under this subsection is a confidential record and
8 may be disclosed only to the parole board, the governor, the pardon advisory board, or
9 their authorized representative. Victims of violent crimes may at the discretion of the
10 parole board, the governor, or the pardon advisory board personally appear and
11 address the parole board, the governor, or the pardon advisory board. Victim
12 testimony and written statements under this subsection are confidential and may be
13 disclosed only to the parole board, the governor, the pardon advisory board, or their
14 authorized representative. Notice must be given by the parole board or, pardon clerk,
15 or authorized representative informing the registered victim of the pending review. The
16 registered victim must be provided notice of the decision of the parole board or of the
17 governor and the recommendations of the pardon advisory board, if any, and, if
18 applicable, notice of the date of the prisoner's release on parole or the prisoner's
19 pardon, conditional pardon, reprieve, commutation, or remission of fine. Notice must
20 be given within a reasonable time after the parole board or the governor makes a
21 decision but in any event before the parolee's or pardoned prisoner's release from
22 custody.
